                immuneResponse:           "A clinician states: 'We should not give live attenuated vaccines to any patient on steroids because their immune system is weakened.' Evaluate this clinical reasoning — assess whether it is always, sometimes, or never correct, specify what level of immunosuppression would contraindicate a live vaccine, and explain why the same reasoning would NOT apply to inactivated vaccines.",
                antibioticsAndResistance: "Evaluate the antibiotic prescribing policy: 'To ensure complete bacterial eradication, patients should always continue antibiotics until all symptoms have resolved, even if this extends the prescribed course.' Identify the error in this reasoning, explain the microbiological basis for fixed-duration courses, and assess whether longer courses reduce or increase resistance risk.",
                transmission:             "Evaluate the public health claim: 'Once herd immunity is achieved naturally through infection, vaccination is no longer necessary.' Address the claim using: (a) the distinction between infection-derived and vaccine-derived immunity; (b) the durability of natural vs vaccine immunity for specific diseases; (c) the mortality and morbidity cost of achieving natural herd immunity; (d) the continued risk to immunocompromised individuals.",
                vaccines:                 "A parent reads online that 'the MMR vaccine causes the diseases it protects against because it contains live viruses.' Evaluate this claim scientifically — explain what 'attenuated' means at the molecular and phenotypic level, specify the frequency of vaccine-associated adverse events compared to natural disease risk, and assess the specific scenario in which live vaccine virus could theoretically cause disease."
